00:05:15.230 --> 00:05:17.510
When we talk about
reading and developing

00:05:17.510 --> 00:05:19.470
and sustaining readers
across a lifespan,

00:05:19.470 --> 00:05:22.070
of course we're beginning in the
youngest years as I mentioned.

00:05:22.070 --> 00:05:24.250
And Mike, I would like to
just start with you talking

00:05:24.250 --> 00:05:26.960
about your work and what
you think is most important

00:05:26.960 --> 00:05:28.740
in the early years.

00:05:28.740 --> 00:05:32.540
&gt;&gt; Mike McGuffee: So we
have been doing this work --

00:05:32.540 --> 00:05:35.420
I've been doing this
work forever.

00:05:35.420 --> 00:05:38.660
Maybe about three decades
and I've done a lot

00:05:38.660 --> 00:05:40.670
of work in Indian country.

00:05:40.670 --> 00:05:44.140
And what I realized
in doing that work was

00:05:44.140 --> 00:05:48.480
when I felt was the fundamental
problem was access to books

00:05:48.480 --> 00:05:51.770
which then I developed
a formula just

00:05:51.770 --> 00:05:54.820
like Stephen [phonetic] thinking
about what is the formula

00:05:54.820 --> 00:05:57.210
for this and we look at this now

00:05:57.210 --> 00:05:59.690
as a problem that's
-- it's three parts.

00:05:59.690 --> 00:06:04.470
It's -- it is access but
you also have to have access

00:06:04.470 --> 00:06:08.150
to relevant books and
then that's not enough.

00:06:08.150 --> 00:06:10.110
You have to have engagement
around those books.

00:06:10.110 --> 00:06:12.350
So it's access, relevance,
and engagement

00:06:12.350 --> 00:06:16.540
to me is the way I frame a
problem and think about it.

00:06:16.540 --> 00:06:22.230
And with access, our company
has developed a definition

00:06:22.230 --> 00:06:25.920
for what we consider to be
the deserts or book scarcity.

00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:28.070
We've actually mapped
the United States

00:06:28.070 --> 00:06:33.630
down the census track using NAP
[phonetic] data and census data.

00:06:33.630 --> 00:06:40.170
And we think that 75% of
the United States has homes

00:06:40.170 --> 00:06:43.670
with less than 100 books.

00:06:43.670 --> 00:06:45.660
And that's a staggering number

00:06:45.660 --> 00:06:51.380
and we're actually rebuilding
our map so that we can see --

00:06:51.380 --> 00:06:54.200
so that you working in your
communities can interact

00:06:54.200 --> 00:06:56.250
with that map.

00:06:56.250 --> 00:06:58.650
The next thing is relevance.

00:06:58.650 --> 00:07:01.580
And there's lots of ways
to think about relevance

00:07:01.580 --> 00:07:05.370
but one is there's more than
200 languages that are spoken

00:07:05.370 --> 00:07:09.000
in the United States,
indigenous and immigrant.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:14.860
And so we need to figure out
how to create greater relevance.

00:07:14.860 --> 00:07:17.690
So in our library, we
have an online library

00:07:17.690 --> 00:07:22.020
for emergent readers essentially
and we write the books

00:07:22.020 --> 00:07:24.240
in English but we
also narrate them.

00:07:24.240 --> 00:07:27.690
Right now, our narrations are
getting close to 40 languages.

00:07:27.690 --> 00:07:30.110
We're doing a project with
the [inaudible] River Indian

00:07:30.110 --> 00:07:34.640
Community South of Phoenix
where they're writing books

00:07:34.640 --> 00:07:37.360
that celebrate their
culture and language.

00:07:37.360 --> 00:07:39.810
Over a four year
period, we're trying

00:07:39.810 --> 00:07:42.540
to write 100 little
emergent books with them.

00:07:42.540 --> 00:07:44.960
And then we're trying to
get 100 of those books

00:07:44.960 --> 00:07:47.750
into the homes across
the community.

00:07:47.750 --> 00:07:50.910
So relevance is an
important piece.

00:07:50.910 --> 00:07:53.740
And then last is engagement.

00:07:53.740 --> 00:07:57.660
And it's one thing to get
books into kids' homes

00:07:57.660 --> 00:08:00.360
but it's another
thing to inspire them

00:08:00.360 --> 00:08:02.240
to become lifelong readers.

00:08:02.240 --> 00:08:07.770
And we find that is really
challenging for us to think

00:08:07.770 --> 00:08:11.190
about the -- we talked --
this morning about a culture

00:08:11.190 --> 00:08:13.820
of literacy, a culture
of reading.

00:08:13.820 --> 00:08:16.370
It's nurturing a
culture of reading

00:08:16.370 --> 00:08:18.520
in the communities
where we work.

00:08:18.520 --> 00:08:20.840
So that engagement
piece is really --

00:08:20.840 --> 00:08:23.550
has really been interesting
to us.

00:08:23.550 --> 00:08:27.610
We looked at NAP data and
found something amazing.

00:08:27.610 --> 00:08:29.930
The interesting thing
about NAP is

00:08:29.930 --> 00:08:32.610
that they have been
surveying kids forever

00:08:32.610 --> 00:08:36.210
with two questions
that we found useful.

00:08:36.210 --> 00:08:39.230
One they ask how many books
do you have in your home?

00:08:39.230 --> 00:08:42.490
And two, they ask how often
do you choose to read for fun?

00:08:42.490 --> 00:08:46.450
And when you take those two
questions and analyze them,

00:08:46.450 --> 00:08:51.110
what we found was that
if you have 0 to 10 books

00:08:51.110 --> 00:08:55.930
and you never read, about 7% of
that population is proficient

00:08:55.930 --> 00:08:58.140
in reading in the eighth grade.

00:08:58.140 --> 00:09:01.970
When you have 100 books and you
have a daily habit of reading,

00:09:01.970 --> 00:09:06.480
about 70% of those kids are
proficient and the pattern

00:09:06.480 --> 00:09:10.810
across that as you add books,
it improves but you have

00:09:10.810 --> 00:09:12.920
to have books and reading.

00:09:12.920 --> 00:09:15.960
People say to me all the time,
it has to be more than books.

00:09:15.960 --> 00:09:20.230
And the answer is yes, it is
more than books because it has

00:09:20.230 --> 00:09:22.700
to be that those kids read them.

00:09:22.700 --> 00:09:24.920
So when we look at the
kids that have 100 books

00:09:24.920 --> 00:09:26.220
and they say never read.

00:09:26.220 --> 00:09:29.920
Their scores aren't that great
but when they have 100 books

00:09:29.920 --> 00:09:32.290
and they read everyday
it matters.

00:09:32.290 --> 00:09:36.460
So we've looked at this and
kind of made our formula

00:09:36.460 --> 00:09:39.060
about access, relevance,
and engagement.

00:09:39.060 --> 00:09:43.390
The last thing is for when we
think about sustaining readers

00:09:43.390 --> 00:09:47.470
across a lifetime, I
think we have to look

00:09:47.470 --> 00:09:51.500
at our educational system as
a complex adaptive system.

00:09:51.500 --> 00:09:53.760
We have to look at
this as a system

00:09:53.760 --> 00:09:56.190
and Donnelle Meadows [phonetic]
who's a great system --

00:09:56.190 --> 00:09:59.820
was a great systems thinker
said if you really want

00:09:59.820 --> 00:10:02.790
to impact the system, you
got to look at the purpose.

00:10:02.790 --> 00:10:05.480
And not what the
stated purpose is,

00:10:05.480 --> 00:10:07.890
what's the behavior
of the system?

00:10:07.890 --> 00:10:12.870
What I think is going on is that
we have to have a higher purpose

00:10:12.870 --> 00:10:16.080
in our system than
grade level reading.

00:10:16.080 --> 00:10:18.580
We have to have a higher
purpose in our system

00:10:18.580 --> 00:10:21.540
than kindergarten readiness.

00:10:21.540 --> 00:10:23.370
And actually the title

00:10:23.370 --> 00:10:27.700
of our talk is probably
a much greater purpose.

00:10:27.700 --> 00:10:31.070
What would happen if our
educational system thought

00:10:31.070 --> 00:10:35.400
about this and said how do we
sustain readers over a lifetime?

00:10:35.400 --> 00:10:37.220
What if we measured that?

00:10:37.220 --> 00:10:41.540
What if we really thought about
how do you get kids excited

00:10:41.540 --> 00:10:43.740
about reading and
keep them reading?

00:10:43.740 --> 00:10:48.470
So how do we think
about it is start early.

00:10:48.470 --> 00:10:53.300
And we think Frank Smith
once said it's this simple.

00:10:53.300 --> 00:10:57.750
Get a book in a kid's hands that
they want to read and can read

00:10:57.750 --> 00:10:59.800
and when they finish
get another.

00:10:59.800 --> 00:11:02.420
So in some ways,
it's that simple.

00:11:02.420 --> 00:11:08.220
In the complex way, it's we've
got to look at our schools,

00:11:08.220 --> 00:11:11.210
our communities as systems,
and starting having more

00:11:11.210 --> 00:11:12.970
of a systems perspective.

