00:11:58.560 --> 00:12:01.630
that Mike just talked about and
also that came up this morning

00:12:01.630 --> 00:12:07.090
but as they apply to the teen
reader phase of the lifespan.

00:12:07.090 --> 00:12:12.570
So with engagement being
really the key piece to if --

00:12:12.570 --> 00:12:14.310
you know, we all
know that in order

00:12:14.310 --> 00:12:17.710
to become a stronger reader, you
have to read and that in order

00:12:17.710 --> 00:12:21.240
to read meaningfully,
to actually read deeply,

00:12:21.240 --> 00:12:22.540
and make meaning from text,

00:12:22.540 --> 00:12:24.050
you have to be engaged
with the reading.

00:12:24.050 --> 00:12:28.730
And so the key factors that
play to that engagement are

00:12:28.730 --> 00:12:34.140
as Mike said relevance
and also choice.

00:12:34.140 --> 00:12:36.280
And I know that came up a
lot this morning as well.

00:12:36.280 --> 00:12:40.480
So we need to be able to provide
teen readers who are struggling

00:12:40.480 --> 00:12:43.380
with reading with books
that they can connect to.

00:12:43.380 --> 00:12:46.540
Books that are culturally
relevant for a diverse,

00:12:46.540 --> 00:12:50.210
wide range of readers where
they can really see themselves

00:12:50.210 --> 00:12:52.570
reflected in the books
that they're reading.

00:12:52.570 --> 00:12:56.050
And books that are relevant
to their age and interests.

00:12:56.050 --> 00:12:59.920
So books where they can
read about other characters

00:12:59.920 --> 00:13:02.580
who are their own age, who are,
you know, dealing with things

00:13:02.580 --> 00:13:04.150
that they're dealing with.

00:13:04.150 --> 00:13:07.090
And then choice which again
came up a lot this morning.

00:13:07.090 --> 00:13:11.170
That it's one of the biggest
factors in reading meaningfully

00:13:11.170 --> 00:13:13.610
and that a huge number
of students report

00:13:13.610 --> 00:13:15.530
that they cannot
find enough books

00:13:15.530 --> 00:13:17.040
that they actually like to read.

00:13:17.040 --> 00:13:22.790
And so these, you know, two
pieces, relevance and choice,

00:13:22.790 --> 00:13:25.920
become actually, you know,
a unique challenge on a lot

00:13:25.920 --> 00:13:28.340
of levels when you look at
the teen reader audience

00:13:28.340 --> 00:13:33.710
that is struggling
because if you are 12 or 16

00:13:33.710 --> 00:13:36.870
and you're reading at a
first or a third grade level,

00:13:36.870 --> 00:13:39.950
you're never going to be
excited by books written

00:13:39.950 --> 00:13:42.230
for first or third graders.

00:13:42.230 --> 00:13:43.530
Books that are written

00:13:43.530 --> 00:13:45.710
for elementary school
students are never going

00:13:45.710 --> 00:13:47.010
to be interesting to you.

00:13:47.010 --> 00:13:51.080
Not only will they be boring
and kind of totally irrelevant

00:13:51.080 --> 00:13:52.820
to the things you're working on
and thinking about in your life

00:13:52.820 --> 00:13:56.040
but also embarrassing to
read in front of your peers.

00:13:56.040 --> 00:13:59.150
And so, you know,
how do we address

00:13:59.150 --> 00:14:00.620
that piece of the problem?

00:14:00.620 --> 00:14:03.770
How do we provide enough choices
that these students can find

00:14:03.770 --> 00:14:06.960
that they can like to read
whether it's late elementary

00:14:06.960 --> 00:14:10.100
school, middle school,
or high school or beyond.

00:14:10.100 --> 00:14:12.210
And, you know, we know that
it's a huge number of students

00:14:12.210 --> 00:14:14.320
who fit into this category.

00:14:14.320 --> 00:14:17.330
It's tens of millions
in this country alone.

00:14:17.330 --> 00:14:21.760
So this problem just from a
personal standpoint is one

00:14:21.760 --> 00:14:24.220
that I experienced as a teacher.

00:14:24.220 --> 00:14:27.060
I was a middle school teacher
in Lynn, Massachusetts.

00:14:27.060 --> 00:14:29.190
And most of my teaching
as English

00:14:29.190 --> 00:14:31.320
as a Second Language
as I mentioned.

00:14:31.320 --> 00:14:35.380
Most of students were from the
Dominican Republic or Haiti

00:14:35.380 --> 00:14:39.130
and they were, you
know, sassy and witty

00:14:39.130 --> 00:14:41.530
and mature middle
school students but a lot

00:14:41.530 --> 00:14:43.890
of them were reading at first
and second grade levels.

00:14:43.890 --> 00:14:46.910
And one of my biggest
challenges was, you know,

00:14:46.910 --> 00:14:48.210
access to choices for them.

00:14:48.210 --> 00:14:52.550
Even as the teacher who is
actively pursuing options

00:14:52.550 --> 00:14:54.140
that I could offer them
that would engage them

00:14:54.140 --> 00:14:55.460
in reading so that they'd read.

00:14:55.460 --> 00:14:56.760
So that they'd improve.

00:14:56.760 --> 00:14:58.920
I just couldn't find enough
books to offer a range

00:14:58.920 --> 00:15:00.930
of choices that they
would want to read

00:15:00.930 --> 00:15:02.230
and that they could read.

00:15:02.230 --> 00:15:07.590
And so, just to touch briefly
on Story Shares and what we do.

00:15:07.590 --> 00:15:10.980
We are focused on
finding kind of new ways

00:15:10.980 --> 00:15:12.710
to generate more choices.

00:15:12.710 --> 00:15:15.690
More of these books
that are relevant

00:15:15.690 --> 00:15:17.040
to older students
aged interests,

00:15:17.040 --> 00:15:18.800
culturally relevant for
diverse, you know, learners,

00:15:18.800 --> 00:15:23.720
that are accessible and
approachable in both format

00:15:23.720 --> 00:15:31.310
and also language at a range
of much lower reading levels.

00:15:31.310 --> 00:15:35.350
And so doing, giving
readers books that will kind

00:15:35.350 --> 00:15:37.730
of hook them and give them
the positive associations

00:15:37.730 --> 00:15:41.050
with reading that we all have
and kind of help to erase some

00:15:41.050 --> 00:15:42.570
of those negative ones.

00:15:42.570 --> 00:15:44.210
And so what we do
is we actually tap

00:15:44.210 --> 00:15:46.620
into the community of writers.

00:15:46.620 --> 00:15:49.510
We crowd source these
books by providing --

00:15:49.510 --> 00:15:53.160
we do an annual writing
contest and we provide guidance

00:15:53.160 --> 00:15:56.140
and incentives and an awareness
campaign to get writers

00:15:56.140 --> 00:16:01.280
and educators to contribute to
this new collection of books

00:16:01.280 --> 00:16:02.580
to submit their own stories.

00:16:02.580 --> 00:16:04.070
And then we use those stories.

00:16:04.070 --> 00:16:07.510
We curate them and have them
become part of the collection.

00:16:07.510 --> 00:16:12.440
And again, what we -- you
know we all know to be true is

00:16:12.440 --> 00:16:15.190
that when we can find that
experience with a book,

00:16:15.190 --> 00:16:18.530
that spark of something that
starts with what we love,

00:16:18.530 --> 00:16:20.710
what we care about already,
what we connect with,

00:16:20.710 --> 00:16:26.850
whether it's you know,
baseball or food or gossip.

00:16:26.850 --> 00:16:31.080
That we can start to really --

00:16:31.080 --> 00:16:34.560
sometimes it literally just
takes the one book to realize

00:16:34.560 --> 00:16:37.100
that this is not something --

00:16:37.100 --> 00:16:39.050
you know it's not
that I'm not a reader.

00:16:39.050 --> 00:16:43.120
It's just that I hadn't -- as
come up, I haven't found books

00:16:43.120 --> 00:16:44.460
that really speak to me.

00:16:44.460 --> 00:16:46.630
And so what we see
and what we know is

00:16:46.630 --> 00:16:49.560
that once we can offer
these students choices

00:16:49.560 --> 00:16:52.070
that are meaningful to
them that they can read,

00:16:52.070 --> 00:16:55.410
that kind of destigmatize
their experience with reading,

00:16:55.410 --> 00:16:59.880
not only are they reading
more but also they're talking

00:16:59.880 --> 00:17:02.060
about the books that
they're reading more.

00:17:02.060 --> 00:17:05.340
You know we love hearing from
teachers about, you know,

00:17:05.340 --> 00:17:08.480
you read a new book and then
this is a student who's maybe

00:17:08.480 --> 00:17:10.560
so reluctant and has
struggled so much with reading,

00:17:10.560 --> 00:17:13.030
after they have an experience
with the book that they love,

00:17:13.030 --> 00:17:14.330
they say could we
talk about this?

00:17:14.330 --> 00:17:16.160
You know I want to tell
you about what I read.

00:17:16.160 --> 00:17:19.330
And also can I have
other books like this?

00:17:19.330 --> 00:17:22.600
And not only do they
inspire students to read more

00:17:22.600 --> 00:17:26.900
but also to actually to write.

00:17:26.900 --> 00:17:30.560
We know that sometimes
you can be so inspired

00:17:30.560 --> 00:17:32.580
by something you've
read that you even want

00:17:32.580 --> 00:17:33.880
to kind of write your own.

00:17:33.880 --> 00:17:35.520
Whether it's an adaptation
of that

00:17:35.520 --> 00:17:38.100
or something inspired
by or a sequel.

00:17:38.100 --> 00:17:41.470
And so kind of focusing
on generating

00:17:41.470 --> 00:17:44.200
and distributing more books
that are really relevant

00:17:44.200 --> 00:17:47.090
to a wide range of students
while also being approachable

00:17:47.090 --> 00:17:51.990
to really hook them and then set
them on path of being readers.

00:17:51.990 --> 00:17:53.290
&gt;&gt; Joshua Cramer:
Thanks, Louise.

00:17:53.290 --> 00:17:54.590
Chris?

00:17:54.590 --> 00:17:55.890
&gt;&gt; Christopher Lehman: And
what Louise and I were talking

00:17:55.890 --> 00:17:57.330
about this conversation,
one thing we also touched

00:17:57.330 --> 00:17:59.820
on was just the shame
that can come

00:17:59.820 --> 00:18:03.220
for you being an adolescent
reader who is carrying

00:18:03.220 --> 00:18:04.740
around a book that's Judy Moody

00:18:04.740 --> 00:18:08.090
or something that's not
appropriate for your age level.

00:18:08.090 --> 00:18:10.710
And that's both from the
community that you build

00:18:10.710 --> 00:18:12.010
or don't have in your classroom

00:18:12.010 --> 00:18:14.200
but that affects the
child as well too.

00:18:14.200 --> 00:18:18.250
So I come to this
conversation from K12 pedagogy.

00:18:18.250 --> 00:18:21.900
That's been my experience
nearly working on two decades

00:18:21.900 --> 00:18:23.940
of working as a classroom
teacher

00:18:23.940 --> 00:18:25.570
and then supporting
educators as well.

00:18:25.570 --> 00:18:30.050
I'm also honored to serve
on the board with NCFL.

00:18:30.050 --> 00:18:34.090
And so one conversation
that we often have at NCFL

00:18:34.090 --> 00:18:37.350
with the education work group
that we support with them

00:18:37.350 --> 00:18:39.010
and just in my work in general,

00:18:39.010 --> 00:18:43.530
at the secondary level is
just looking at this pattern

00:18:43.530 --> 00:18:47.180
that continues to play out
where there's kind of two things

00:18:47.180 --> 00:18:48.480
that happen at the same time.

00:18:48.480 --> 00:18:53.220
One is we see this slump in
test scores or in performance

00:18:53.220 --> 00:18:56.680
when kids hit middle school
where students are growing,

00:18:56.680 --> 00:18:58.880
growing, growing across the
elementary years and then

00:18:58.880 --> 00:19:01.100
when we hit secondary there's
like something happens.

00:19:01.100 --> 00:19:03.570
And so many districts have
questions around that.

00:19:03.570 --> 00:19:05.320
You equally like
with the NAP data,

00:19:05.320 --> 00:19:09.620
Common Sense Media organization
has also done some surveys,

00:19:09.620 --> 00:19:11.820
longitudinal surveys
around this as well.

00:19:11.820 --> 00:19:14.270
You see students at the
same time reporting out.

00:19:14.270 --> 00:19:16.610
You can almost correlate
them against each other

00:19:16.610 --> 00:19:20.190
that as there's a slump
in secondary performance,

00:19:20.190 --> 00:19:22.420
there also are kids who
are reading less and less

00:19:22.420 --> 00:19:24.450
as you move up through years.

00:19:24.450 --> 00:19:27.510
And so I say this with love
because I'm an educator myself

00:19:27.510 --> 00:19:30.040
and I love the field
that we're in.

00:19:30.040 --> 00:19:33.530
One challenge for the
literacy community to look at

00:19:33.530 --> 00:19:37.060
and address is that -- to really
be partners with and support

00:19:37.060 --> 00:19:41.630
around is that any teacher
and the vast majority

00:19:41.630 --> 00:19:45.940
of teachers are working
hardest with so little and with

00:19:45.940 --> 00:19:48.040
so much negative attention from
the press and everywhere else.

00:19:48.040 --> 00:19:51.480
But every teacher is using to
their best of ability the tools

00:19:51.480 --> 00:19:53.330
and knowledge that
they already have.

00:19:53.330 --> 00:19:56.520
And there's a tremendous gap
in both professional learning

00:19:56.520 --> 00:19:58.400
for teachers of high quality

00:19:58.400 --> 00:20:01.390
and in pre-service
teacher education programs

00:20:01.390 --> 00:20:03.610
around literacy specifically
especially

00:20:03.610 --> 00:20:05.060
at the secondary level.

00:20:05.060 --> 00:20:07.580
So what you have are
teachers who are often times

00:20:07.580 --> 00:20:09.690
with their full heart
teaching in the way

00:20:09.690 --> 00:20:12.700
that they remember being taught
when they were a kid whether

00:20:12.700 --> 00:20:15.940
that worked for them and
their fellow peers or not.

00:20:15.940 --> 00:20:18.130
And often times, it doesn't.

00:20:18.130 --> 00:20:20.500
And so one challenge we have is

00:20:20.500 --> 00:20:24.720
around choice is also moving
ahead the conversation

00:20:24.720 --> 00:20:27.080
around practice at
the second level.

00:20:27.080 --> 00:20:29.500
We know from numerous
school sites and districts

00:20:29.500 --> 00:20:34.110
that independent reading at this
level is booming and beautiful

00:20:34.110 --> 00:20:35.670
and can grow an entire
communities.

00:20:35.670 --> 00:20:38.850
And really shift everything
from test scores to how students

00:20:38.850 --> 00:20:41.040
and families feel about school.

00:20:41.040 --> 00:20:42.800
The challenge is there
are so many classrooms

00:20:42.800 --> 00:20:45.830
and so many progress through
all those grade levels

00:20:45.830 --> 00:20:48.300
that become based on
just single books.

00:20:48.300 --> 00:20:50.160
So Penny Kiddle who's
an educator and writes

00:20:50.160 --> 00:20:52.790
for the Educator, she
often says, you know,

00:20:52.790 --> 00:20:54.830
here we are especially at this
time right now where there's

00:20:54.830 --> 00:20:57.740
such a boom of middle grade
and young adult literacy

00:20:57.740 --> 00:21:01.360
where we are surrounded
by this endless library

00:21:01.360 --> 00:21:02.660
of incredible books.

00:21:02.660 --> 00:21:03.960
Here we are at the
Library of Congress.

00:21:03.960 --> 00:21:07.120
This incredible library of
amazing books and too often

00:21:07.120 --> 00:21:12.020
in our pedagogical practices, we
boil those down to four or five,

00:21:12.020 --> 00:21:15.050
one perhaps that we all
have to read together.

00:21:15.050 --> 00:21:18.030
And whether that matches your
reading level or your relevance

00:21:18.030 --> 00:21:21.150
or you care about it or not,
this is what we'll do together.

00:21:21.150 --> 00:21:24.780
So one place that we can really
work is to take the research

00:21:24.780 --> 00:21:28.160
and energy that we all have
in this room and beyond,

00:21:28.160 --> 00:21:31.420
and continue to tell the
story of these practices

00:21:31.420 --> 00:21:33.840
with our older students
and with educators

00:21:33.840 --> 00:21:35.210
at upper levels as well.

00:21:35.210 --> 00:21:38.220
And also to consider if
your program focuses more

00:21:38.220 --> 00:21:40.370
specifically at younger grades,

00:21:40.370 --> 00:21:42.590
so much of your practices
translate up.

00:21:42.590 --> 00:21:45.210
It really is the types
of texts that you use

00:21:45.210 --> 00:21:47.610
but the practices are
inherently the same.

00:21:47.610 --> 00:21:50.080
That really is a place that
your organization can look.

00:21:50.080 --> 00:21:51.620
Can we support older students?

00:21:51.620 --> 00:21:54.560
We absolutely can because
it's kind of the same work.

00:21:54.560 --> 00:21:57.380
Then equally that's
one area to focus.

00:21:57.380 --> 00:21:59.590
Another that feels important
because of where we are

00:21:59.590 --> 00:22:01.340
and because we can see
Congress if we just look

00:22:01.340 --> 00:22:04.220
out that window right
there is just to echo --

00:22:04.220 --> 00:22:05.850
I really appreciated Dr. --

00:22:05.850 --> 00:22:07.240
I mean I appreciate
everything Dr. [inaudible] does.

00:22:07.240 --> 00:22:09.210
It was just awesome
to be in the same room

00:22:09.210 --> 00:22:12.140
but his earlier comments around
poverty, poverty, poverty.

00:22:12.140 --> 00:22:15.830
I think we also have to lay
that what goes above that,

00:22:15.830 --> 00:22:18.370
the kind of larger capsule
over poverty, poverty,

00:22:18.370 --> 00:22:22.410
poverty is just the
systemic oppression, racism,

00:22:22.410 --> 00:22:26.940
the way that our society allows
some people to reach poverty,

00:22:26.940 --> 00:22:28.390
and some people not to.

00:22:28.390 --> 00:22:31.330
And some classrooms to be
funded and some not to.

00:22:31.330 --> 00:22:34.190
So one thing that our
organization works really hard

00:22:34.190 --> 00:22:36.420
to do and just want to
suggest as something for all

00:22:36.420 --> 00:22:39.590
of our organizations to
continue do or to consider

00:22:39.590 --> 00:22:43.360
if we don't already, whether
you're non-profit or public,

00:22:43.360 --> 00:22:49.030
is when our families and
students are in jeopardy

00:22:49.030 --> 00:22:51.660
or in need, we have
to find a message

00:22:51.660 --> 00:22:53.500
and support around that as well.

00:22:53.500 --> 00:22:56.540
Because we can support a
reader who is deported.

00:22:56.540 --> 00:22:59.000
We can't support a reader
who's family is not allowed

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:01.120
into the country because
of their religion.

00:23:01.120 --> 00:23:04.020
We can't support a reader
who doesn't feel safe

00:23:04.020 --> 00:23:07.810
in their classroom because
they have a food shortage.

00:23:07.810 --> 00:23:13.020
And one thing that we've
done in our organization,

00:23:13.020 --> 00:23:14.320
the Educator Collaborative,

00:23:14.320 --> 00:23:18.840
and continue do is really
first working on our approach

00:23:18.840 --> 00:23:23.070
and the way that we enter
communities but also to continue

00:23:23.070 --> 00:23:27.360
to speak out when our students
and families need those too.

00:23:27.360 --> 00:23:31.600
So thinking about when is the
time to talk, it was probably

00:23:31.600 --> 00:23:34.250
like 10 years ago but
when things come up,

00:23:34.250 --> 00:23:35.550
that's another form

00:23:35.550 --> 00:23:37.680
of supporting our secondary
learners is making sure

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:40.300
that we're supporting their
safety and their livelihoods

00:23:40.300 --> 00:23:42.960
and their family's
safety as well.

