00:25:56.870 --> 00:25:58.170
for sale on our website.

00:25:58.170 --> 00:26:00.350
We're processing about
a million books a week

00:26:00.350 --> 00:26:03.400
from those 8,000
supply partners.

00:26:03.400 --> 00:26:04.880
And we're doing everything
that we can

00:26:04.880 --> 00:26:08.220
to increase the availability
of books globally

00:26:08.220 --> 00:26:12.060
and we're just very
thankful to be here today.

00:26:12.060 --> 00:26:13.360
&gt;&gt; Joshua Cramer:
Well, thanks Dustin.

00:26:13.360 --> 00:26:15.470
And just to throw
another question your way.

00:26:15.470 --> 00:26:17.160
You know with all of
your diverse experiences

00:26:17.160 --> 00:26:21.320
across the world, are there any
stories from the book giveaways

00:26:21.320 --> 00:26:25.210
or anything that you would want
to share with the group today?

00:26:25.210 --> 00:26:26.510
&gt;&gt; Dustin Holland: Sure.

00:26:26.510 --> 00:26:29.490
We have a lot of stories
as you can imagine.

00:26:29.490 --> 00:26:32.230
I've been with the
company about 15 years.

00:26:32.230 --> 00:26:33.530
Some of those stories

00:26:33.530 --> 00:26:35.920
if I shared them I
would get in trouble.

00:26:35.920 --> 00:26:37.550
When I first started
with the company,

00:26:37.550 --> 00:26:38.850
none of us were married.

00:26:38.850 --> 00:26:40.150
None of us had kids.

00:26:40.150 --> 00:26:42.570
And thankfully, a lot of us
are married now and have kids

00:26:42.570 --> 00:26:45.960
and have calmed down
a little bit.

00:26:45.960 --> 00:26:52.030
But a lot of great stories
over the years but probably one

00:26:52.030 --> 00:26:58.730
of my most recent favorites
is a book mobile that --

00:26:58.730 --> 00:27:00.440
Better World Books is
a for-profit company

00:27:00.440 --> 00:27:03.790
but we had a supporter
of the company

00:27:03.790 --> 00:27:07.940
that donated a book mobile
to us about a year ago.

00:27:07.940 --> 00:27:12.530
So through this book
mobile, we've been able to go

00:27:12.530 --> 00:27:17.040
out into the community and
we show up at a school,

00:27:17.040 --> 00:27:20.200
prescheduled visits, and kids
come out from the classroom.

00:27:20.200 --> 00:27:21.520
They board the book mobile.

00:27:21.520 --> 00:27:22.820
We call it Wordsworth
[phonetic].

00:27:22.820 --> 00:27:25.290
Holds about 3500 books.

00:27:25.290 --> 00:27:28.160
And the kids get on the book
mobile and they can pick

00:27:28.160 --> 00:27:30.990
as many books as they
want from the book mobile.

00:27:30.990 --> 00:27:33.930
So I think we've donated
a lot of books to a lot

00:27:33.930 --> 00:27:36.050
of organizations
around the world

00:27:36.050 --> 00:27:39.420
but actually doing it ourselves
with the book mobile has kind

00:27:39.420 --> 00:27:43.750
of made it a little more
tangible to us as opposed

00:27:43.750 --> 00:27:47.090
to us donating, you know,
hundreds of thousands of books

00:27:47.090 --> 00:27:49.410
to an organization and
we're not on the ground

00:27:49.410 --> 00:27:50.710
to help distribute those books.

00:27:50.710 --> 00:27:56.450
So to be able to see the kids
jump for joy and trade books

00:27:56.450 --> 00:27:58.860
and sometimes they
fight over books,

00:27:58.860 --> 00:28:01.470
it's really, really powerful.

00:28:01.470 --> 00:28:02.790
&gt;&gt; Joshua Cramer: Thank you.

00:28:02.790 --> 00:28:07.250
For the rest or panel, if you
could share what you think

00:28:07.250 --> 00:28:09.400
or some of what you think
might be the biggest mistakes

00:28:09.400 --> 00:28:11.610
that we could make along
the way as we try to develop

00:28:11.610 --> 00:28:13.920
and sustain readers
across a lifetime

00:28:13.920 --> 00:28:15.830
and I mean I could
start with you, Chris.

00:28:15.830 --> 00:28:17.610
Maybe we'll just
come back this way.

00:28:17.610 --> 00:28:18.910
&gt;&gt; Christopher Lehman: Sure.

00:28:18.910 --> 00:28:22.020
I mean I guess one -- I was
kind of touching on in terms

00:28:22.020 --> 00:28:24.740
of pedagogy but it can really
be for anyone is trying

00:28:24.740 --> 00:28:28.350
to over prescribe --
okay I'll [inaudible] --

00:28:28.350 --> 00:28:29.910
I'll go for it this way.

00:28:29.910 --> 00:28:31.250
I think there's two extremes.

00:28:31.250 --> 00:28:33.500
One is to over prescribe
the sorts of reading

00:28:33.500 --> 00:28:36.390
that we'd expect secondary
students to do instead

00:28:36.390 --> 00:28:39.610
of allowing choice
but there's --

00:28:39.610 --> 00:28:41.270
perhaps that is equally
dangerous

00:28:41.270 --> 00:28:46.150
but also a consideration is
that as students are aging

00:28:46.150 --> 00:28:49.250
and the amount of complexity
and texts that are around them,

00:28:49.250 --> 00:28:51.900
we also have to pair
that independent reading

00:28:51.900 --> 00:28:53.570
and lots more reading time

00:28:53.570 --> 00:28:56.630
with really thoughtful
responsive instruction as well.

00:28:56.630 --> 00:28:58.510
So that our students are --

00:28:58.510 --> 00:29:00.310
we're meeting them
where they are in terms

00:29:00.310 --> 00:29:01.610
of their literacy development

00:29:01.610 --> 00:29:05.410
but then we're adding
instruction on top of that.

00:29:05.410 --> 00:29:08.520
As I think was mentioned earlier
today, one thing that plays

00:29:08.520 --> 00:29:10.200
out across the entire U.S.

00:29:10.200 --> 00:29:13.850
when it comes K12 education is
really a student's reading level

00:29:13.850 --> 00:29:16.510
becomes the ceiling for
which they will perform

00:29:16.510 --> 00:29:17.810
on standardized tests.

00:29:17.810 --> 00:29:19.910
And these aren't just
tests of literacy.

00:29:19.910 --> 00:29:21.900
These are tests in
social studies and science

00:29:21.900 --> 00:29:23.200
and other content areas too

00:29:23.200 --> 00:29:26.200
because every test is
ultimately a test of reading.

00:29:26.200 --> 00:29:27.500
Can you read the instructions?

00:29:27.500 --> 00:29:28.800
Can you read through it?

00:29:28.800 --> 00:29:31.040
So a student who is reading far
below grade level is not going

00:29:31.040 --> 00:29:32.990
to pass most tests.

00:29:32.990 --> 00:29:35.290
They will perform far
below grade level.

00:29:35.290 --> 00:29:37.870
Students that are approaching
grade level as readers tend

00:29:37.870 --> 00:29:39.750
to approach grade
levels as readers.

00:29:39.750 --> 00:29:42.930
You can give students --
you can do running records

00:29:42.930 --> 00:29:44.230
or give them some sort

00:29:44.230 --> 00:29:46.630
of reading assessment just
before a standardized assessment

00:29:46.630 --> 00:29:48.260
and the two will line up.

00:29:48.260 --> 00:29:51.840
What becomes more of a challenge
is as students are then reading

00:29:51.840 --> 00:29:56.870
at or above grade level, that
becomes kind of the opportunity

00:29:56.870 --> 00:29:59.770
but it's then their ability to
think critically on top of that

00:29:59.770 --> 00:30:01.390
that becomes equally important.

00:30:01.390 --> 00:30:04.420
So I think one challenge
is not --

00:30:04.420 --> 00:30:06.620
one, finding the right
balance between those two.

00:30:06.620 --> 00:30:09.070
Like providing expert
instruction while not

00:30:09.070 --> 00:30:10.370
over prescribing it.

00:30:10.370 --> 00:30:12.030
And then just to briefly say,

00:30:12.030 --> 00:30:16.470
I think the other is not
providing enough opportunity

00:30:16.470 --> 00:30:20.040
for educators and in a
larger community conversation

00:30:20.040 --> 00:30:23.130
in literacy as well
to really collaborate

00:30:23.130 --> 00:30:25.180
and communicate together.

00:30:25.180 --> 00:30:28.190
We know that increasingly
the amount of PD dollars,

00:30:28.190 --> 00:30:30.680
professional development dollars
but just the amount of time

00:30:30.680 --> 00:30:33.480
that educators have during the
day to collaborate and talk

00:30:33.480 --> 00:30:36.630
about instruction in many
districts just increasingly

00:30:36.630 --> 00:30:39.310
shrinks as money gets
put in other places.

00:30:39.310 --> 00:30:42.160
So creating that
time to communicate

00:30:42.160 --> 00:30:44.920
and collaborate together which
when I think about the variety

00:30:44.920 --> 00:30:49.520
of partnerships and
organizations here to also think

00:30:49.520 --> 00:30:53.000
about ways that you
can invite educators

00:30:53.000 --> 00:30:54.850
from a school that's local

00:30:54.850 --> 00:30:57.320
to where ever your
organization operates

00:30:57.320 --> 00:30:59.420
to be a part of that as well.

00:30:59.420 --> 00:31:02.120
Educators are in this
field because they care

00:31:02.120 --> 00:31:03.520
so deeply about your kids.

00:31:03.520 --> 00:31:05.210
They will show up
at the laundromat.

00:31:05.210 --> 00:31:07.270
They will go wherever
you invite them to go

00:31:07.270 --> 00:31:09.810
with almost no pay,
if no pay at all.

00:31:09.810 --> 00:31:12.200
They just need the
invitation and to really know

00:31:12.200 --> 00:31:15.830
that that opportunity is
going to help their kids.

00:31:15.830 --> 00:31:20.050
Educators, we call our students
kids because they are our kids.

00:31:20.050 --> 00:31:21.690
We really feel that
way about them.

00:31:21.690 --> 00:31:25.280
So I think providing more
opportunities for collaboration

00:31:25.280 --> 00:31:28.660
with your local schools
and educators within it.

00:31:28.660 --> 00:31:31.940
If we don't do that as the
problem, if we do it supports.

00:31:31.940 --> 00:31:33.240
&gt;&gt; Joshua Cramer: Thanks, Chris.

00:31:33.240 --> 00:31:34.540
Louise? Mike?

00:31:34.540 --> 00:31:37.140
Things to add about
mistakes that we could make.

00:31:37.140 --> 00:31:38.440
&gt;&gt; Louise Baigelman: Sure.

00:31:38.440 --> 00:31:42.490
Yes. I think right alongside
kind of over prescribing

00:31:42.490 --> 00:31:44.900
that one of the mistakes
that we can make

00:31:44.900 --> 00:31:47.440
and that well intentioned
parents

00:31:47.440 --> 00:31:50.380
and educators sometimes
mistakes is over judging

00:31:50.380 --> 00:31:52.180
around what students
are reading.

00:31:52.180 --> 00:31:54.790
So when we talk about choice
which again we've talked

00:31:54.790 --> 00:31:57.820
about a lot, it has to be
real, authentic choice.

00:31:57.820 --> 00:32:02.250
It can't be, you know, choice
but between these two books

00:32:02.250 --> 00:32:03.960
or it has to be non-fiction.

00:32:03.960 --> 00:32:09.280
It really needs to be rigorous
at exactly your level or above.

00:32:09.280 --> 00:32:13.100
You know we -- or even
format or the type

00:32:13.100 --> 00:32:14.400
of thing you're reading.

00:32:14.400 --> 00:32:15.700
Is that really something
you think,

00:32:15.700 --> 00:32:17.000
you know, that you should read?

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:21.380
I think that we have a tendency
to push towards certain types

00:32:21.380 --> 00:32:23.100
of books or certain
types of contents

00:32:23.100 --> 00:32:28.050
and that's not a bad angle
but for students especially

00:32:28.050 --> 00:32:30.120
in the teen, kind of middle
school, high school range

00:32:30.120 --> 00:32:32.800
where judgment is a
very big part of life,

00:32:32.800 --> 00:32:36.100
having it be really
open around, you know,

00:32:36.100 --> 00:32:39.460
whether it's graphic novels
or comic books as we talked

00:32:39.460 --> 00:32:44.720
about earlier or cookbooks if
you love food or blog posts

00:32:44.720 --> 00:32:46.020
if that's something that --

00:32:46.020 --> 00:32:49.790
we talk about as Story Shares
is any reading is good reading.

00:32:49.790 --> 00:32:52.270
And so audio books.

00:32:52.270 --> 00:32:54.510
You know reading is about
making meaning from text.

00:32:54.510 --> 00:32:55.810
So if you really struggle

00:32:55.810 --> 00:32:59.440
with the text piece audio books
are a great place to start.

00:32:59.440 --> 00:33:01.710
Using that as a point
of entry as a hook

00:33:01.710 --> 00:33:03.240
so that the student
can feel connected

00:33:03.240 --> 00:33:05.450
to reading whatever the
format, whatever the topic.

00:33:05.450 --> 00:33:09.230
And then you can scaffold up
there and move towards kind

00:33:09.230 --> 00:33:12.790
of the goal of whatever
higher level content is.

00:33:12.790 --> 00:33:16.190
I think that, kind of, we have
to avoid too much judgment

00:33:16.190 --> 00:33:19.360
when really encouraging
students to engage with reading

00:33:19.360 --> 00:33:22.600
and find a point of
connection with it.

00:33:22.600 --> 00:33:24.090
&gt;&gt; Mike McGuffee: I think
I'll build off of that.

00:33:24.090 --> 00:33:26.560
The -- I think the biggest
mistake that's going

00:33:26.560 --> 00:33:29.660
on right now is we have a one
dimensional model of reading

00:33:29.660 --> 00:33:31.700
in our educational system.

00:33:31.700 --> 00:33:33.760
And it's around proficiency.

00:33:33.760 --> 00:33:38.100
And I love the work of
Richard Ryan and Ed Deecy.

00:33:38.100 --> 00:33:42.040
They're two psychologists that
have self determination theory.

00:33:42.040 --> 00:33:43.490
And in their theory, they think

00:33:43.490 --> 00:33:47.840
that what we're intrinsically
motivated to be is competent

00:33:47.840 --> 00:33:52.240
at what we do, whatever it is,

00:33:52.240 --> 00:33:55.390
autonomy is important,
and relatedness.

00:33:55.390 --> 00:33:58.090
So competence, autonomy,
and relatedness.

00:33:58.090 --> 00:34:02.810
If we had those three dimensions
in our literacy thinking

00:34:02.810 --> 00:34:06.470
in schools, we would
value autonomy a lot more

00:34:06.470 --> 00:34:09.680
and what they argue is that
when you have an over dominance

00:34:09.680 --> 00:34:12.330
of one thing, you can
thwart the others.

00:34:12.330 --> 00:34:16.900
I think that's what's happening
because we have this, again,

00:34:16.900 --> 00:34:19.810
if we don't have this
purpose that we want kids

00:34:19.810 --> 00:34:22.410
to be avid readers
and lifelong readers,

00:34:22.410 --> 00:34:26.480
then we can start focusing
on grade level reading.

00:34:26.480 --> 00:34:28.750
Over dominance one dimension

00:34:28.750 --> 00:34:32.360
of proficiency can cause
autonomy to be thwarted.

00:34:32.360 --> 00:34:35.200
It can also cause
relatedness to be thwarted.

00:34:35.200 --> 00:34:39.990
Lois said it earlier about
that reading is about identity.

00:34:39.990 --> 00:34:41.620
It's about agency.

00:34:41.620 --> 00:34:44.720
Those are -- that's
autonomy and relatedness.

00:34:44.720 --> 00:34:49.820
And so I think we as educators,
we tend to talk to each other

00:34:49.820 --> 00:34:52.880
and I think we need to branch
out and start looking at some

00:34:52.880 --> 00:34:56.500
of these psychologists
and the systems thinkers

00:34:56.500 --> 00:34:59.490
that can help us kind
of maybe reframe this.

00:34:59.490 --> 00:35:00.790
&gt;&gt; Christopher Lehman:
Can we also add to that?

00:35:00.790 --> 00:35:03.230
So if third grade
guarantee is a mistake

00:35:03.230 --> 00:35:05.640
that many states are
implementing the expectation

00:35:05.640 --> 00:35:08.370
that by third grade, you
have to read a certain way

00:35:08.370 --> 00:35:10.760
or you're held back or lots
of terrible things happen

00:35:10.760 --> 00:35:14.100
to you along those same lines.

00:35:14.100 --> 00:35:15.400
&gt;&gt; Joshua Cramer: Absolutely.

00:35:15.400 --> 00:35:17.160
I have to admit there's
a little bit of bias

00:35:17.160 --> 00:35:19.650
